Why the Three‑disc Greatest Hits is rejected: Although the Greatest Hits set is warm and vocal‑forward and offers breadth and replay value, it is fundamentally a multi‑disc, career‑spanning singles anthology — i.e., a single‑artist greatest‑hits compilation. That format conflicts with my stated dislike of singles-driven, patched compilations that undermine album-level cohesion. Even with careful sequencing, a three‑disc hits package emphasizes breadth of eras and singles over a unified album statement, so it doesn’t satisfy my core preference for an album that rewards full-playback listening as a cohesive experience. Therefore, despite its vocal-forward mastering and variety, it’s the less appropriate choice compared with the focused, album-oriented Too Low for Zero.

