- Why Animals is less aligned: Animals scores strongly on some technical boxes I like — preserved analogue tape warmth, wide uncompressed dynamics, roomy stereo imaging, and deep low end — and it offers coherent front‑to‑back sequencing and collector‑grade mastering. However, it is explicitly an album‑length progressive suite built around extended instrumental interplay and cohesive long‑form structure, not a collection of tight 3–5 minute riff‑driven singles or concise songcraft. My stated gravitation toward punchy, riff‑driven rock singles, minimal‑overdub grit, and concise arrangements conflicts with Animals’ extended progressive format. Also, part of my dislike is for arrangements that trade punch and focused low‑end weight for long, piano/keyboard‑led or sprawling instrumental passages; even though Animals’ piano/keys are described as well‑integrated, the dominant long‑form, studio‑crafted progressive approach makes it less likely to deliver the tight, riff‑forward, single‑centric energy I favor.
Conclusion
Given the emphasis in my preferences on concise, riff‑driven songs with punchy bass/drums, guitar‑forward gritty performances, roomy but not hyper‑spotlit vocals, preserved headroom and tight sequencing, Jagged Little Pill aligns more closely with those priorities. Animals, while excellent on dynamics, warmth and front‑to‑back cohesion, is a long‑form progressive suite that diverges from my core preference for compact, riff‑driven singles and minimal‑overdub grit, so I reject it in favor of Jagged Little Pill.

